<troubleshooting id="troubleshooting-6781" xml:lang="en-us" class="- topic/topic troubleshooting/troubleshooting "><title class="- topic/title ">Unable to execute tests on localhost with TestCloud Tunnel</title><shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "/><troublebody class="- topic/body troubleshooting/troublebody "><condition class="- topic/section troubleshooting/condition "><p class="- topic/p "> Execution with <ph conkeyref="name-variables/name-variable-testcloud" class="- topic/ph "/> and <uicontrol conkeyref="tc-ui-text/tc-ui-testcloud-tunnels" class="+ topic/ph ui-d/uicontrol "/> fails on locally hosted sites. In this case, the report screenshot might show that the test fails to load the local site as follows: <image href="image/Unable_to_load_localhost.png" class="- topic/image "/></p></condition><troubleSolution class="- topic/bodydiv troubleshooting/troubleSolution "><cause class="- topic/section troubleshooting/cause "><p class="- topic/p ">The workaround is to set an additional domain for your local address (127.0.0.1) and use that domain, instead of <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">localhost</codeph>, in your tests.</p><p class="- topic/p ">In most operating systems, domains can be set in the <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">hosts</codeph> file. The following remedy shows you how to set the additional domain.</p></cause><remedy class="- topic/section troubleshooting/remedy "><steps-unordered class="- topic/ul task/steps-unordered "><step class="- topic/li task/step "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">On Windows</b>:</cmd><substeps class="- topic/ol task/substeps "><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Navigate to the <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">C:\Windows\System32\Drivers\etc\hosts</codeph> file. </cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><image href="image/Windows_hosts_file.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open the file in an editor with administrator privilege.</cmd></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">In the file, add another domain for <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">127.0.0.1</codeph>.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info ">For example, we add the <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">mydomain</codeph> domain name.<image href="image/Notepad_hosts_file.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open the file again to verify that the changes have been updated.</cmd></substep></substeps></step><step class="- topic/li task/step "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">On macOS</b>:</cmd><substeps class="- topic/ol task/substeps "><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">In your terminal, open the hosts file with an editor. </cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info ">Here we use <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">nano</codeph> to open the host file at <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">/private/etc/hosts</codeph>.<codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">sudo nano /private/etc/hosts</codeblock></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Add the new domain name into the file.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">127.0.0.1       mydomain</codeblock><image href="image/macOS_terminal_hosts_file.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Save the file. With <codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph ">nano</codeph>, use <userinput class="+ topic/ph sw-d/userinput ">Ctrl</userinput> + <userinput class="+ topic/ph sw-d/userinput ">X</userinput> then <userinput class="+ topic/ph sw-d/userinput ">Y</userinput> to save the file.</cmd></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open the file again to verify the changes.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">cat /private/etc/hosts  </codeblock><image href="image/macOS_hosts_file_updated.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep></substeps></step><step class="- topic/li task/step "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">On Linux:</b></cmd><substeps class="- topic/ol task/substeps "><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">In your terminal, open the hosts file with an editor.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">sudo nano /etc/hosts</codeblock></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Add the new domain name to the file.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">127.0.0.1       mydomain</codeblock><image href="image/ubuntu_nano_hosts_file.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep><substep class="- topic/li task/substep "><cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open the file again to verify the changes.</cmd><info class="- topic/itemgroup task/info "><codeblock class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock ">cat /etc/hosts</codeblock><image href="image/ubuntu_hosts_file_edited.png" width="500" class="- topic/image "/></info></substep></substeps></step></steps-unordered></remedy></troubleSolution></troublebody></troubleshooting>